{"v":1,"id":"VGqG5uaj5eGnNNUhT5ZB","createdAt":"2026-07-09T02:05:40.329Z","app":{"name":"AxiVale","version":"1.3.4"},"kind":"conversation","title":"of last monday's raid","turns":[{"userText":"of last monday's raid","agentText":"\n\nOne raid last Monday, and it was a winning night. Let me pull Not Haro's recent commanding history to set the baseline.\n\nNot Haro (harasho.4281) commanded five nights in this window. Let me pull the other four for the trend.\n\nNot Haro's last-Monday raid (July 6) was his cleanest \"real fight\" night in six weeks — 71% fight-win rate and a 1.63 K/D over a grinding 45 fights. Here's the commander review.\n\n## Not Haro — Commander Review (last Monday, July 6)\n\n**The night:** Not Haro (harasho.4281, tagging on his support Troubadour) led a 32-player squad through **45 fights, going 32–13 (71% wins)** on 2026-07-06 in gw2eww/fight-reports. Squad K/D was **1.63** (481 enemy deaths vs 296 squad deaths), with **868 enemy downs to 575 squad downs**. That's his highest fight volume and best real-fight win rate of the last six weeks — a clear rebound after a rough 06-20 (0.75 K/D). Only one run was published for that date; no runs were skipped.\n\nAcross his five Not Haro nights in this window, results swing hard with the matchup — a blowout on 05-25 (11.8 K/D vs even numbers) and a brutal outnumbered loss on 05-30 (0.45 K/D, 39 vs 73). Last Monday sits firmly on the winning side and, unlike 05-25, it was earned over a long grind rather than a farm.\n\n{{figure}}\n\nHere's how last Monday compares to his recent nights on squad health:\n\n{{figure}}\n\n| Date | Fights | W–L | Squad K/D | Squad deaths | Squad downs | Down→death |\n|------|-------:|:---:|----------:|-------------:|------------:|-----------:|\n| 05-25 | 11 | 11–0 | 11.78 | 32 | 114 | 28% |\n| 05-30 | 12 | 1–11 | 0.45 | 370 | 629 | 59% |\n| 06-06 | 18 | 11–7 | 1.59 | 306 | 514 | 60% |\n| 06-20 | 21 | 12–9 | 0.75 | 340 | 551 | 62% |\n| **07-06** | **45** | **32–13** | **1.63** | **296** | **575** | **51%** |\n\n*(Down→death = squad deaths ÷ squad downs — lower is better; more downs getting rallied. Full per-player rows are in Actions.)*\n\n**Strengths**\n- **Sustained aggression that stayed clean.** 45 fights is more than double any other recent night, yet he posted the *fewest* squad deaths (296) of the five — low-feed leading at high tempo.\n- **Best earned win rate of the stretch.** 71% fight wins over a full night, with a smaller 32-man squad, beats his 06-06 (61%) and 06-20 (57%) nights on more bodies.\n- **Good kill conversion on the enemy.** 868 enemy downs turned into 481 kills — the squad cleaved out its pressure rather than letting enemies rally.\n\n**Coaching points**\n- **Rally your own downs faster.** 51% of squad downs became deaths last Monday — better than 06-06/06-20 (~60%) but well off the 28% he hit on his 05-25 blowout. That's the single biggest lever: tighter peel/cleave on downed allies converts a 1.63 K/D night into a 2.0+ one.\n- **Press the winning nights with more bodies.** He ran 32 here vs 40–46 when he tags his bigger nights. When the fights are going his way, scaling the squad up (without loosening the ball) compounds the advantage.\n- **Matchup discipline on the bad draws.** The 0.45 and 0.75 nights were largely outnumbered/uneven — not a leadership failure, but choosing when to disengage and reset vs. keep committing is where those nights bleed downs.\n\n**Bottom line:** double down on the high-tempo, low-death aggression — that's what made last Monday work. The one habit to change is down-to-death conversion: get the squad rezzing/cleaving its own downs harder, and his best nights stop needing a numbers advantage to look dominant.","filedAt":"7:01 PM","tools":[{"name":"axibridge_runs_list"},{"name":"axibridge_commander_stats","display":{"kind":"table","data":{"title":"Commanders","columns":[{"key":"account","label":"Commander"},{"key":"fightsLed","label":"Fights led"},{"key":"wins","label":"W"},{"key":"losses